Planung

Protokoll
Fr die Datenbertragung und Langzeitspeicherung kommt die Protokollspezikation
FTLight zum Einsatz, die im Rahmen des Europischen Radioastronomieklubs (ERAC) fr
global/Cosmos vernetzte Systeme entwickelt wurde. Diese ist die Grundlage fr eine
Klasse von Anwendungen FTLightApp, welche ebenfalls eine registrierte Trademark ist:!
https://ftlightapp.eu!
Prototyp
Eine 6m hohe Groundplane fr 7/14/21/28 MHz liefert die Antennensignale fr eine
Testinstallation, welche ber ein 40m langes Aircell-7 Kabel an die Hardware in einem
Schaltkasten auf freiem Feld weitergeleitet werden. Die Stromversorgung erfolgt ber
Solarzellen und der Internetzugang ist mit einem mobilen Router realisiert.!
Der Prototyp ist Teil einer greren Installation auf einem Feld in Mecklenburg-
Vorpommern zur Bestimmung des solaren Anteils am Klimawandel auf der Erde: !
https://wegalink.eu/mvp!
Aktuelles
In Vorbereitung zur Ergnzung des Bandkonzeptes mit den 2m/70cm-Bereichen sollen die
Mglichkeiten der ZMOD SDR Module zur eventuellen Integration dieser Frequenzen mit der
dritten und achten Nyquist-Zone untersucht werden.!
Fr ein erstes Band (vermutlich 20m) sollen die Bandpasslter fr die Vor- und Hauptselektion
entworfen und durch Simulation getestet werden.!
Der FTLight-Framework soll fr eine sichere Verbindung von verteilten Modulen ber das
Internet ergnzt werden.!
Eine erste Topologie mit einem Modul fr Datenerfassung (Eclypse Z7), einem Modul fr die
Langzeitspeicherung und einem GUI-Modul soll erstellt werden.!

Fragen an die KI Systeme (Prompt)
Prompt 1:!
The signals from a 6m high ground plane antenna resonant at 7/14/21/28 MHz at a low
interference location should be provided to 4 separate SDR channels by a lter board for a remote
access over the internet. !
There are the following questions: !
A - In addition to the four main radio amateur bands 7000..7200kHz, 14000..14350kHz,
21000..21450kHz and 28000..29690kHz also other amateur radio frequencies 1810..2000kHz,
3500..3800kHz, 10100..10150kHz, 18068..18168kHz, 24890..24990kHz and 50000..52000kHz
should be combined with the main frequency bands in a multi-bandpass design with one input
port (ground plane antenna) and four output ports for four SDR channels. What would be a
suitable combination of those additional frequencies with the main frequency bands? !
B - How could the lter circuitry look like and what tools could be used to develop, verify and test
the design? !
C - Each of the SDR channels has a 14-bit resolution and a +/-0.5V input range. What specic
amplication factors should be used in each of the frequency ranges for receiving as low as
possible input signals without exceeding the SDR input range with a more than 95% probability
based on average long-term signal statistics in those frequency bands? What would be the
resulting sensitivity of each frequency band?!
Prompt 2:!
Grouping adjacent bands for channels seems to be advantageous. A channel broadband lter will
pre-select frequencies for !
ch1: 1.8-7.2MHz, !
ch2: 10.1-14.35MHz, !
ch3:18.0-25.0MHz and !
ch4: 28-52MHz. !
A problem exists with radio stations and other strong signals outside intended bands which would
limit the feasible amplication for not clipping them. Therefore, main frequency band selection will
be inserted only after a pre-amplier which role is to compensate for antenna matching and pre-
selection losses and for improving noise gures. !
There will be another band-specic amplier after main bandpasses which should bring the signal
level up such that there is a 95% probability for not getting into clipping signals after combining
the bandpass signals in each channel. !
How should the gain of those ampliers after pre-selection as well as before combining signals in
each channel be chosen in order to meet the clipping constraint for each frequency band on the
input of the SDR channels that sample signals at 125 MSample/s and what would be the resulting
minimal signal level in each band?!
Prompt 3:!
It should be admitted that an Eclypse Z7 with a ZMOD SDR will be used which features a clipping
threshold slightly higher than 1 Vpp on a 50 Ohm input resistance which translates approximately
to a +4dBm hard clipping threshold. !
How will the lter and gain concept be aected by that detail (if at all)?!
Zusammenfassung: SDR Multi-Band Filter Design
Grundproblem!
- ADC Limit: +4 dBm Clipping!
Systemarchitektur
Antenna Splitter(-6dB) Broadband Filter(-2dB)
Pre-Amp Bandpass Filter(-3dB) Band-Amp
Combiner(-4dB) ADC
Zielpegel (um Clipping zu vermeiden):!
- 3-Band-Kanle: -5 dBm pro Band am Combiner -9.8 dBm am ADC!
- 2-Band-Kanle: -3 dBm pro Band am Combiner -10 dBm am ADC!
- Safety Margin: 13-14 dB bis Clipping!

Pre-Amp Design!
- Zweck: Nur Verluste kompensieren, nicht maximieren!
- Begrndung: Out-of-band Interferer (AM/SW Broadcast) vermeiden!
- Komponenten: MAR-8+, ERA-3+, ERA-5+!
Band-Amp Design!
- Moderate Gain (14-22 dB): GALI-74+ (single stage)!
- High Gain (24-31 dB): 2 MAR-6 mit Dmpfungspads dazwischen!
- Dmpfungspads: 3 dB zwischen Stufen fr Stabilitt!
Combiner-Wahl!
- Empfehlung: Passive Combiner (-4 dB Loss)!
- Aktive Combiner abgelehnt: !
- +3-5 dB NF Addition!
- IP3 begrenzt (+20-30 dBm)!
- Komplexitt ohne Vorteil bei atmosphrischem Rauschen!
20m Band Problem!
- Nur +18 dB Gain (niedrigster Wert) wegen Overload-Risiko!
- Resultat: Receiver-limitierte Sensitivitt (-123 dBm vs. -135 dBm atmosphrisch)!
- Lsung: Schaltbarer +10 dB Gain fr schwache Signale!
Sensitivitt (Final)!
- System NF: ~7 dB!
- MDS: -123 dBm (2.5 kHz BW, 10 dB SNR)!
- Limitierung:!
- 160-80m: Atmosphrisch limitiert (wie gewnscht)!
- 40m, 30m, 17-6m: Receiver gut genug!
- 20m: 10 dB Dezit AGC/Switch empfohlen!
Komponenten-Auswahl!
- Pre-Amps: MAR-8ASM+ (+8dB), ERA-5SM+ (+12dB)!
- Band-Amps: GALI-74+ (moderate), 2 MAR-6SM cascaded (high gain)!
- Stabilitt: 3 dB Pads zwischen Kaskaden!
Design-Verikation!
1. Filter-Simulation (QUCS/LTspice): >35 dB Rejection!
2. Amplier K-Factor: >1 (Stabilitt)!
3. Two-Tone IMD Test: IP3 > +20 dBm!
4. Power Supply Isolation: separate Regulatoren + Ferrite Beads!
Fazit!
- Design erfllt +4 dBm Clipping-Constraint mit 13-14 dB Margin!
- Sensitivitt ausreichend fr alle Bnder (auer 20m AGC-Option)!
-Trade-o: Overload-Schutz vs. Weak-Signal-Performance!
Implementierungs-Details!
Broadband Filter Design!
Channel 1 (1.8-7.2 MHz):!
- Typ: 5-pole Chebyshev highpass + lowpass combination!
- Komponenten: !
- Highpass (fc = 1.5 MHz): blocks AM broadcast!
- Lowpass (fc = 8 MHz): attenuates higher bands!
- Erwartete Performance:!
- Insertion loss: 1.5-2 dB!
- Rejection at 1 MHz (AM BC): >40 dB!
- Rejection at 10 MHz: >35 dB!
Channel 2 (10.1-18.2 MHz):!
- Typ: 5-pole bandpass!
- Kritisch: SW broadcast bei 11.6-12.1 MHz liegt innerhalb des Passbands!
- Lsung: Zustzlicher Notch-Filter bei 11.8 MHz (30-40 dB Dmpfung)!
- Twin-T Notch oder helical resonator!
- Q-Factor: 20-30!
- Alternative: Breiterer Bandpass (9.5-15 MHz) mit steileren Flanken!
Channel 3 (21.0-25.0 MHz):!
- Typ: 6-pole bandpass!
- Problem: SW broadcast bei 19.0, 21.5, 25.7 MHz!
- Lsung: !
- Mehrere Notch-Filter oder!
- Akzeptanz hherer Pre-Amp Kompression (Pre-Amp IP3 > +30 dBm ntig)!
- Bandbreite: 7 MHz erfordert moderate Q-Werte (Q 3-5)!
Channel 4 (28-52 MHz):!
- Typ: 5-pole highpass + lowpass!
- Kritisch: FM broadcast rejection (88-108 MHz)!
- Anforderung: >50 dB Dmpfung bei 88 MHz!
- Komponenten:!
- 7-pole Chebyshev lowpass (fc = 60 MHz)!
- Steilheit: >12 dB/octave!
- Eventuell zustzlicher Stub-Filter bei 100 MHz!
Bandpass Filter Design (nach Pre-Amp)!
Fr alle Bnder: 7-pole elliptic lters (bester Trade-o zwischen Steilheit und Insertion Loss)!
Beispiel 40m Band (7.0-7.2 MHz):
Design Parameters:
- Center frequency: 7.1 MHz
- Bandwidth: 200 kHz (Q = 35.5)
- Passband ripple: 0.1 dB
- Stopband attenuation: >60 dB at 300 kHz
- Insertion loss target: <3 dB
LC Values (50, normalized dann skaliert):
C1 = 680 pF L1 = 7.5 H
C2 = 1200 pF L2 = 4.2 H
C3 = 820 pF L3 = 6.8 H
(Trap fr Stopband: L4||C4 bei 6.5 MHz und 7.7 MHz)
Praktische Hinweise:!
- Induktoren: Coilcraft 1812CS oder Maxi-Spring air-core!
- SRF (Self-Resonant Frequency) >30 MHz!
- Q-Factor >80 bei HF!
- Kondensatoren: ATC100B oder Kemet C0G/NP0!
- Low ESR (<0.1)!
- Temperaturstabilitt 30 ppm/C!
- Tuning: Variable capacitors (Johanson trimmer) fr Abgleich!
- 5-15 pF Trimmbereich!
- Initial alignment mit VNA!
Amplier Kaskadierung (High-Gain Pfade)!
Beispiel: 160m Band (+31 dB bentigt)
Schaltung:
BPF MAR-6SM (+18dB) 3dB Pad MAR-6SM (+18dB) 2dB Pad Combiner
Stage 1 (MAR-6SM):
- Gain: +18 dB
- NF: 2.5 dB
- IP3: +30 dBm (output)
- Input matching: 50 (interne Schaltung)
- Output matching: Series L (22 nH) + Shunt C (47 pF)
3 dB Pad (-attenuator):
- R1 = R3 = 18 (series)
- R2 = 150 (shunt)
- Zweck: Stabilitt, VSWR improvement, IP3 boost
Stage 2 (MAR-6SM):
- Identisch zu Stage 1
- Eingangsisolation durch Pad verbessert Stabilitt
2 dB Pad (-attenuator):
- R1 = R3 = 12
- R2 = 220
- Finale Anpassung an Combiner
Gesamt-Performance:
- Gain: 18 - 3 + 18 - 2 = +31 dB
- NF: ~3.5 dB (dominiert von Stage 1)
- IP3 (output): ~+28 dBm
-IP3 (input referred): +28 - 31 = -3 dBm
Stabilitt sicherstellen:!
- Oscillation Check: S11, S22 < -10 dB ber 1-100 MHz!
- K-Factor Test: K > 1.5 fr alle Frequenzen!
- Manahmen bei Instabilitt:!
- 10-22 series resistor am Eingang!
- Ferrite bead (BLM18 series) in Versorgungsleitung!
- Zustzliche Entkopplung: 100nF || 10F || 100F nahe IC!
PCB Layout Guidelines
Kritische Aspekte:
1. Ground Plane:!
- Durchgehende Masseche auf Layer 2 (bei 4-Layer PCB)!
- Keine Unterbrechungen unter Signalpfaden!
- Via-stitching entlang Signalwege (/20 Abstand bei hchster Frequenz)!
- Fr 52 MHz: /20 30 cm / 20 = 1.5 cm Vias alle 1 cm!
2. Controlled Impedance Traces:!
- 50 microstrip fr alle RF-Verbindungen!
- FR4, h = 1.6mm, r = 4.3: Breite 3 mm!
- Lnge minimieren (< 5 cm zwischen Stufen)!
- Keine rechten Winkel (45 chamfers)!
3. Component Placement:
Signalfluss (linear, keine Loops):
Input BBF Pre-Amp [BPF1 Amp1]
[BPF2 Amp2] Combiner Output
[BPF3 Amp3]
- Abstand zwischen Pfaden: >2 cm (Isolation >40 dB)
- Shielding zwischen Kanlen: Cu-tape walls oder SMD shield cans
4. Power Supply Distribution:!
- Separate Regulatoren fr jeden Kanal (z.B. ADP150, LT1763)!
- Star-Point Grounding vom zentralen Power-Entry!
- Decoupling pro IC:
VCC Pin 100nF (0402, close) 10F (0805, 5mm away) Regulator
Ferrite bead (BLM18) zwischen Regulator und IC-Gruppe
- Avoid ground loops: Single-point ground am Eingangs-Connector
5. Filter Construction:!
- LC-Filter mit hohem Q:!
- Induktoren: Stehend montiert (minimiert parasitre C)!
- Kondensatoren: Direkt auf Pads, kurze Verbindungen!
- Guard traces zwischen L und C (verhindert parasitre Kopplung)!
- Layout-Simulation: Sonnet Lite oder ADS Momentum!
- Validierung von S-Parameters vor Fertigung!
Combiner Design Details
Resistive Combiner (Wilkinson-artig vereinfacht):
Fr Ch1 (3 Bnder):
160m path [50]
[Isolation R: 150 zwischen Ports] 50 output
80m path [50]
40m path [50]
Jeder 50 Widerstand:
- 2 100 parallel (2W metal film, <1% tolerance)
- Low inductance package (z.B. KOA RK73)
Isolation widerstnde (150):
- Zwischen jedem Port-Paar
- Verhindert Intermodulation zwischen Bndern
- 1/4W ausreichend (geringe Verlustleistung)
Performance:
- Insertion loss: 10log(3) 4.8 dB (theoretisch)
- Praktisch: ~5 dB (resistor losses)
- Isolation zwischen Ports: >20 dB
-VSWR: <1.3:1 an allen Ports
Alternative: Diplexer/Triplexer (verlustrmer):
Fr przise Frequenztrennung:!
Ch1 Beispiel:
160m (1.8-2.0 MHz) Lowpass fc=2.5 MHz
80m (3.5-3.8 MHz) Bandpass 3.0-4.2 MHz Summer Output
40m (7.0-7.2 MHz) Highpass fc=6.0 MHz
Vorteile:
- Insertion loss: ~2 dB (statt 5 dB)
- Bessere Isolation (>40 dB)
- Weniger IMD (keine gemeinsame Resistor-Pfade)
Nachteile:
- Komplexes Design (3-4 mehr Bauteile)
- Kritisches Tuning erforderlich
-Grerer PCB-Bereich
Empfehlung fr Prototyp: Resistiver Combiner!
- Einfach, vorhersagbar, breitbandig!
- 5 dB Loss durch hhere Band-Amp Gains kompensierbar!
- Fr nale Version: Diplexer evaluieren!
Switchable Gain fr 20m Band!
Implementierung (RF-Relay-basiert):
Path A: Direct (0 dB)
20m BPF output
RELAY Combiner
Path B: +10 dB Amp
[MAR-3SM]
Relay: Omron G6K-2F-Y (latching, low capacitance)
- Insertion loss: <0.3 dB
- Isolation: >40 dB bis 1 GHz
- Switching time: 5 ms (acceptable)
- Control: GPIO vom FPGA (3.3V logic)
Control Logic (im FPGA):
1. Kontinuierliches Peak-Monitoring am ADC
2. Wenn Peak > -10 dBm fr >1s: Switch zu Path A (direct)
3. Wenn Peak < -30 dBm fr >10s: Switch zu Path B (amp)
4. Hysterese verhindert Flapping
Alternative: PIN-Diode Switch (MA4GP907)
- Schneller (s), aber hherer Insertion Loss (~1 dB)
-Bentigt bias tee und DC-Kontrolle

Impact auf MDS:

Schritt-fr-Schritt Alignment:!
Phase 1: Filter Charakterisierung (vor Einbau)
1. Broadband Filter Test:
VNA Setup: Port 1 Filter Port 2
- Measure S21 (insertion loss) und S11 (return loss)
- Verify:
* Passband: S21 > -2.5 dB
* Ripple: < 1 dB peak-to-peak
* Return loss: S11 < -15 dB in passband
* Stopband rejection: >30 dB at specified frequencies
Falls auer Spec:
- Trimmer adjustment (falls vorhanden)
- Component tolerance check (messen mit LCR meter)
- Layout parasitic analysis (re-simulate)
2. Bandpass Filter Test:
VNA Setup: Identisch
- 3 dB bandwidth check: sollte 10% von Design sein
- Center frequency: justieren mit trimmer capacitors
- Shape factor (60dB BW / 3dB BW): sollte <3:1 sein
Tuning Prozedur:
a) Zuerst Low-side trimmer: fr untere 3dB Punkt
b) Dann High-side trimmer: fr obere 3dB Punkt
c) Iterativ optimieren bis symmetrisch
d) Dokumentieren: Foto + S-Parameter speichern
Phase 2: Amplier Modul Test

- Group delay: <50 ns variation ber Band

- Kein Oszillieren bei keiner Lastbedingung
- Falls instabil: add series R (10) oder shunt C (10pF)
4. Band Amplifier Test:
Signal Generator Amp Power Meter + Spectrum Analyzer
Gain Compression Test:
- Input power sweep: -40 dBm bis 0 dBm (in 5 dB steps)
- Record output power
- 1 dB compression point: where output deviates 1 dB from linear
- Verify P1dB > -5 dBm (input referred)
Example Data:

Phase 3: Intermodulation Distortion (IMD) Test
5. Two-Tone IMD Test:
Setup:
SigGen1 (f1) -6dB
Combiner DUT Spectrum Analyzer
SigGen2 (f2) -6dB
Fr 20m Band (Ch2):
f1 = 14.100 MHz, f2 = 14.150 MHz

- Fundamental tones: f1, f2 at ~-20 dBm (after system gain)
- IMD3 products:
* 2f1-f2 = 14.050 MHz
* 2f2-f1 = 14.200 MHz
Calculate:
IMD3_level (dBc) = (IMD3_power) - (Fundamental_power)
Acceptance Criteria:
- IMD3 < -50 dBc fr normal operation
- IMD3 < -40 dBc minimum (mit reduced gain acceptable)

Phase 4: System Integration Test
6. Combined Channel Test:
Signal injection: Antenna port
Monitoring: All 4 ZMOD ADC outputs via FPGA
Test Signals:
a) Single-tone sweep:
- 1.8 MHz bis 52 MHz in 100 kHz steps
- Input level: -60 dBm (reprsentativ fr schwache Signale)
- Verify alle Bnder empfangen Signal in korrektem Channel
b) Multi-band simultaneous:

* Keine IMD products zwischen Bndern

c) Strong signal handling:

7. Noise Figure Measurement:
Equipment: Noise source (ENR 15 dB) + Spectrum Analyzer
Y-Factor Method:
- Connect noise source zu System input
- Measure noise power:
* P_hot (noise source ON): example -65 dBm
* P_cold (noise source OFF): example -72 dBm
Calculate:
Y = P_hot / P_cold = 10^((65(72))/10) = 10^0.7 = 5.01
ENR = 15 dB (noise source spec)
NF = ENR 10log(Y1) = 15 10log(4.01) = 15 6.0 = 9.0 dB
Repeat fr alle 4 channels, document results
Phase 5: Dynamic Range Verication
8. Spurious-Free Dynamic Range (SFDR):
Setup: Signal Generator Channel FFT analysis in FPGA
Procedure:
- Input: Two-tone signal at -30 dBm each
- Capture ADC data: 1M samples
- Perform 8192-point FFT
- Measure:
* Fundamental peaks: should be ~60-70 dB above noise floor
* Highest spur (IMD3 or harmonics): measure level
SFDR = (Fundamental level) (Highest spur level)
Target: SFDR > 80 dB (for 14-bit ADC)
Typical: SFDR 75-85 dB (limited by ADC nonlinearity)
If SFDR < 70 dB:
- Check for ADC clocking issues (jitter)
- Verify ADC reference voltage stability
- Check for ground loops (digital/analog isolation)
9. Sensitivity Measurement:
Setup: Signal Generator mit calibrated attenuator
Procedure fr jedes Band:
a) Set signal at band center, -100 dBm
b) Demodulate in FPGA (SSB demodulator, 2.5 kHz BW)
c) Measure SNR at audio output
d) Decrease signal level until SNR = 10 dB
e) Record this level as MDS (Minimum Detectable Signal)
Expected MDS: -121 to -126 dBm (depending on NF optimization)
Compare to theoretical:
MDS_theoretical = -174 + 10log(BW) + NF + SNR_min
= -174 + 34 + 9 + 10 = -121 dBm
Deviation < 3dB akzeptabel
Deviation > 5 dB troubleshooting erforderlich
Troubleshooting wenn MDS schlechter als erwartet:
- Verify NF measurement (wiederholen mit noise source)
- Check for RF leakage (shield effectiveness)
- Measure DC bias currents (compare to datasheet)
- Inspect solder joints (cold joints erhhen losses)

Setup: Place assembly in temperature chamber
Test Cycle:
- Start at 25C, stabilize for 30 min
- Ramp to 60C over 30 min
- Hold 60C for 2 hours
- Ramp to 0C over 30 min
- Hold 0C for 2 hours
- Return to 25C
Monitor during cycle:
- Gain variation per band (should be <1 dB)
- Center frequency drift (should be <0.1% = 7 kHz @ 7 MHz)
- Noise figure change (should be <1 dB)

If frequency drift > 0.1%:
- Use C0G/NP0 capacitors (verified?)
- Temperature-compensate LC tanks (add N750 caps)

11. Burn-In Test:
Duration: 48 hours continuous operation
Conditions: T_ambient = 40C (worst case)
Input stimulus: Multi-tone signal covering all bands
- Each tone at -40 dBm
- Pseudo-random modulation (simulate real traffic)
Monitor every 6 hours:
- Gain per band (log to file)
- Supply currents (detect component degradation)
- Output spectrum (check for new spurs)
Acceptance: No parameter change >2 dB over 48h
Early failure indicators:
- Increasing DC current component stress

Advanced Optimization Techniques
Active Splitter Implementation
**Detailed Design fr 4-Way Active Splitter:**
Schematic:
Antenna Input (50) [Matching] GALI-74+ [4-way resistive divider]
Ch1-4 outputs
Matching Network (optimal NF):
- Input: Series L1 = 220 nH (adds inductive reactance)!
- Shunt C1 = 100 pF (resonates with package parasitics)!
- Provides Zs,opt 20-j30 for GALI-74 @ 14 MHz!
GALI-74+ Specications:
- Gain: +23 dB typ. @ 7 MHz!
- NF: 3 dB typ.!
- IP3 (output): +38 dBm!
- Current: 90 mA @ 5V!
Output Network:
- Each output: 200 series resistor (forms 4-way divider)!
- Combined parallel impedance: 200 || 200 || 200 || 200 = 50!
- Provides 50 output impedance per channel!
- Each channel sees 12 dB loss (4-way split = 6 dB + resistive loss)!
Net Performance:
- System gain: +23 dB (GALI) -12 dB (divider) = +11 dB!
- System NF: 3 dB + (12-1)/23 = 3 + 0.48 3.5 dB!
- Eective "splitter loss": 3.5 - 11 = -7.5 dB (improvement!)!
Stability Enhancements:
- Input series resistor: 10 (damping)!
- Ferrite bead in supply: BLM18PG121 (120 @ 100 MHz)!
- Decoupling: 100nF || 10F || 100F (3-stage)!
- Guard ground vias around GALI-74 (every 2mm)!
Thermal Management:
- GALI-74 dissipation: 5V 90mA = 450 mW!
- Thermal vias: 20 0.3mm direct to ground plane!
- Eective JA: 60C/W T_rise = 27C (acceptable)!
Alternative IC: SPF5189Z (lower NF option)
- Gain: +20 dB!
- NF: 0.6 dB (excellent!)!
- But: IP3 = +25 dBm (12 dB worse than GALI-74)!
- Trade-o: Better sensitivity vs. worse overload!
-Recommendation: Use GALI-74 for amateur radio (strong signal environment)!
**Comparative Analysis: Passive vs. Active Splitter**
| Parameter | Passive Splitter | Active Splitter (GALI-74)|
|-----------|-----------------|---------------------------|
| Loss/Gain | -6 dB | +11 dB |
| NF contribution| 6 dB | 3.5 dB |
| Effective impact| -6 dB |+7.5 dB (+13.5 dB improvement!)|
| Isolation |>20 dB (resistive)|>30 dB (gain stage + divider)|
| IP3 (output)| N/A (passive) | +38 dBm |
| IP3 (input ref)| N/A | +38 - 23 = +15 dBm |
| Power consumption| 0 W | 0.45 W |
| Cost | $10 | $25 |
| Complexity| Low | Medium |

Diplexer/Triplexer Alternative zu Resistive Combiner
**Ch1 Triplexer Design (160m/80m/40m):**
Topology: Parallel LC traps + summation network
Branch 1 (160m path):!
[Input] Lowpass (fc = 2.2 MHz, 5-pole) [Summing junction]!
Components:!
L1 = 3.3H, C1 = 1800pF!
L2 = 2.7H, C2 = 1200pF!
L3 = 3.3H, C3 = 1800pF!
Insertion loss: ~1.5 dB!
Rejection @ 3.5 MHz: >45 dB!
Rejection @ 7.0 MHz: >60 dB!
Branch 2 (80m path): !
[Input] Bandpass (3.2-4.0 MHz, 7-pole elliptic) [Summing junction]!
Center: 3.65 MHz, Q = 12!
Components:
Series arms: L = 4.7H, C = 470pF!
Shunt arms: L = 2.2H, C = 820pF!
Traps at 2.0 MHz and 7.0 MHz!
Insertion loss: ~2.0 dB!
Rejection @ 1.9 MHz: >50 dB!
Rejection @ 7.0 MHz: >55 dB!
Branch 3 (40m path):
[Input] Highpass (fc = 6.0 MHz, 5-pole) [Summing junction]!
Components:!
C1 = 680pF, L1 = 0.82H!
C2 = 470pF, L2 = 1.2H!
C3 = 680pF, L3 = 0.82H!
Insertion loss: ~1.5 dB!
Rejection @ 3.8 MHz: >50 dB!
Rejection @ 1.9 MHz: >65 dB!
Summing Junction:
All three branches Star connection Output impedance 50!
Isolation resistors (optional): 150 between each pair!
Total network impedance maintained by conjugate matching!
Performance Summary:
- Total insertion loss per path: 1.5-2.0 dB (vs. 4.8 dB resistive)!
- Inter-band isolation: >45 dB (vs. 20 dB resistive)!
- IMD reduction: ~10 dB better (less common path nonlinearity)!
- Size: ~3 larger PCB area!
- Tuning: Critical (requires VNA alignment)!
-Cost: ~$50 in components (vs. $5 resistive)!
**Trade-off Decision Matrix:**
| Factor | Weight | Resistive Score | Diplexer Score | Weighted Difference |
|--------|--------|----------------|-----------------|---------------------|
| Insertion Loss|30%| 5/10 (-5dB) | 9/10 (-2dB) | +1.2 |
| Isolation | 20% | 6/10 (20dB). | 9/10 (45dB) | +0.6 |
| Cost | 15% | 9/10 ($5). | 4/10 ($50) | -0.75 |
| Complexity| 15% | 9/10 (simple) | 3/10 (critical) | -0.9 |
| Size | 10% | 8/10 (compact) | 4/10 (large) | -0.4 |
| Reliability| 10%| 9/10 (robust) | 7/10 (tuning drift)| -0.2 |
| **Total Score**|| **7.1/10** | **6.85/10** | -0.25 |
**Decision:** **Use resistive combiner for prototype**
- Simpler, more predictable
- Adequate performance with adjusted band-amp gains
- Diplexer can be retrofit later if needed
For **production version** (after prototype validation):
- Evaluate diplexer if sensitivity proves marginal
- 3 dB insertion loss improvement 3 dB less band-amp gain needed
- Lower IMD from better isolation
Noise Source Characterization (Detailed)
**Proper Noise Figure Measurement Technique:**
Equipment Setup:
- Noise source: HP 346B (ENR = 15.0 dB @ 7 MHz, calibrated)!
- Spectrum analyzer: R&S FSH4 or similar!
- Adapter: N-type to SMA (veried low-loss)!
- Power supply for DUT: Linear regulated, <10 mV ripple!
Calibration Procedure:
1. Connect noise source directly to spectrum analyzer!
2. Set: Center = 7.1 MHz, Span = 100 kHz, RBW = 10 kHz, VBW = 10 kHz!
3. Measure Phot and Pcold at analyzer input:!
Phot,ref = -75.2 dBm (example, your value will vary)
Pcold,ref = -90.3 dBm (thermal noise oor)!
!
4. Calculate eective ENR:!
ENReective = Phot,ref - Pcold,ref = -75.2 - (-90.3) = 15.1 dB
(Close to spec 15.0 dB, conrms calibration)
DUT Measurement:
1. Insert DUT between noise source and analyzer
2. Measure with same settings:
Phot,DUT = -52.8 dBm (example)!
Pcold,DUT = -67.4 dBm (example)
3. Calculate DUT gain:
GDUT = Pcold,DUT - Pcold,ref = -67.4 - (-90.3) = 22.9 dB!
(Should match expected gain 1 dB)!
!
4. Calculate Y-factor:!
Y = 10^((Phot,DUT - Pcold,DUT)/10)!
= 10^((-52.8 - (-67.4))/10)!
= 10^1.46 = 28.8!
!
5. Calculate NF:!
NF_DUT = ENR - 10log(Y - 1)!
= 15.0 - 10log(27.8)!
= 15.0 - 14.4 = 0.6 dB!
!
Wait, this seems too good! Recheck:!
- Verify noise source is ON (LED indicator)!
- Check cable connections (loose = error)!
- Repeat measurement 3 times, average!
Typical Results for MAR-8 Pre-Amp:
- Measured NF: 2.5-3.0 dB (datasheet: 2.8 dB typ.)!
- Gain: 8 0.5 dB!
- Bandwidth: at 0.5 dB from 1.8-30 MHz!
Uncertainty Analysis:
- ENR uncertainty: 0.3 dB (from calibration cert)!
- Spectrum analyzer accuracy: 0.5 dB!
- Mismatch uncertainty: 0.2 dB (with || < 0.2)!
- Total uncertainty: (0.3 + 0.5 + 0.2) = 0.6 dB!
Report NF as: NF = 2.8 0.6 dB @ 7 MHz!
Firmware Implementation (FPGA/Zynq)
**Key DSP Functions for Multi-Band SDR:**!
1. Per-Channel DDC (Digital Down-Converter)
vhdl
[Output Buer] DMA to ARM processor!
Resource Utilization (per channel, Zynq Z7020):
- CIC Filter: ~800 LUTs, 400 FFs, 5 DSP48 slices!
- NCO (32-bit): ~300 LUTs, 200 FFs!
- Complex Mixer: 4 DSP48 slices (Icos, Isin, Qcos, Qsin)!
- FIR Filter: 127 taps 64 DSP48 (symmetric, half-band)!
- Total per channel: ~1200 LUTs, ~600 FFs, ~73 DSP48!
- 4 channels: ~4800 LUTs (14%), ~2400 FFs (3.5%), ~292 DSP48 (133% problem!)!
DSP48 Limitation Solution:
- Time-multiplex FIR lters (4:1 sharing)!
- Process samples in rotation: Ch1 Ch2 Ch3 Ch4 repeat!
- Clock FIR at 4 rate (1 MSPS 4 MSPS)!
-Reduces DSP48 usage: 64 shared + 35 CIC = 79 DSP48 total !
2. AGC (Automatic Gain Control)
c
// ARM processor code (Linux userspace or bare-metal)!
#dene AGCATTACKTIMEMS 10 // Fast response to strong signals
#dene AGCDECAYTIMEMS 100 // Slower return to normal gain!
#dene TARGETLEVELDBM -10 // Target ADC level!
#dene MAXGAINDB 10 // For 20m switchable path!
#dene MINGAINDB 0 // Direct path!
typedef struct {!
oat currentgaindb;!
oat peakleveldbm;!
uint32t peakholdcounter;
bool overloaddetected;!
} agcstatet;!
agcstatet agcch[4];
void agcprocess(int channel, oat measuredpeakdbm) {!
agcstatet *agc = &agcch[channel];
// Update peak detector with decay
if (measuredpeakdbm > agc->peakleveldbm) {
agc->peakleveldbm = measuredpeakdbm;
agc->peakholdcounter = AGCATTACKTIMEMS;!
} else if (agc->peakholdcounter > 0) {!
agc->peakholdcounter--;!
} else {!
// Exponential decay!
oat decayfactor = exp(-1.0 / AGCDECAYTIMEMS);!
agc->peakleveldbm = agc->peakleveldbm * decayfactor +
measuredpeakdbm * (1 - decayfactor);!
}!
!
// Calculate error!
oat errordb = agc->peakleveldbm - TARGETLEVELDBM;
// Gain adjustment
if (errordb > 3.0) {!
// Too hot, reduce gain!
agc->currentgaindb -= 1.0;!
if (agc->currentgaindb < MINGAINDB) {!
agc->currentgaindb = MINGAINDB;!
agc->overloaddetected = true;
}
} else if (errordb < -3.0 && !agc->overloaddetected) {
// Too weak, increase gain
agc->currentgaindb += 0.5; // Slower increase
if (agc->currentgaindb > MAXGAINDB) {
agc->currentgaindb = MAXGAINDB;
}
}
// Clear overload ag if level drops signicantly
if (agc->peakleveldbm < TARGETLEVELDBM - 10.0) {
agc->overloaddetected = false;!
}!
!
// Apply gain change to hardware (relay control for 20m)!
if (channel == 1) { // Ch2, 20m band!
gpiosetrelay(agc->currentgaindb > 5.0); // HIGH = +10dB amp!
}!
}!
// Called every 10ms from timer interrupt!
void agcupdateall(void) {!
for (int ch = 0; ch < 4; ch++) {!
// Read peak detector from FPGA register!
uint16t peakraw = readfpgaregister(PEAKDETECTORBASE + ch*4);!
oat peakdbm = adccountstodbm(peakraw);
agcprocess(ch, peak_dbm);!
}!
}!
3. Peak Detector (FPGA implementation)
vhdl
-- Simplied VHDL for peak detection!
-- Runs at ADC clock rate (125 MHz)!
entity peakdetector is
generic (
DATAWIDTH : integer := 14;!
HOLDTIME : integer := 1250000 -- 10ms @ 125MHz
);
port (
clk : in stdlogic;!
rst : in stdlogic;
datain : in signed(DATAWIDTH-1 downto 0);
peakout : out unsigned(DATAWIDTH-1 downto 0);
peakvalid : out stdlogic
);
end peakdetector;!
architecture rtl of peakdetector is
signal peakreg : unsigned(DATAWIDTH-1 downto 0) := (others => '0');
signal holdcounter : integer range 0 to HOLDTIME := 0;
signal absdata : unsigned(DATAWIDTH-1 downto 0);
begin
-- Absolute value
absdata <= unsigned(datain) when datain >= 0 else!
unsigned(-datain);
process(clk)
begin
if risingedge(clk) then!
if rst = '1' then!
peakreg <= (others => '0');
holdcounter <= 0;!
peakvalid <= '0';
else
-- Update peak
if absdata > peakreg then
peakreg <= absdata;
holdcounter <= HOLDTIME;
peakvalid <= '0';!
elsif holdcounter > 0 then
holdcounter <= holdcounter - 1;
peakvalid <= '0';!
else!
-- Hold time expired, output valid!
peakvalid <= '1';
peakreg <= (others => '0'); -- Reset for next cycle!
holdcounter <= HOLDTIME;!
end if;!
end if;!
end if;!
end process;!
!
peakout <= peakreg;!
!
end rtl;!
Python/C++ code for real-time spectrum display!
Using GNU Radio or custom Qt application!
import numpy as np!
from scipy import signal!
import pyqtgraph as pg!
from PyQt5 import QtCore!
class MultiBandWaterfall:!
def init(self):!
self.channels = 4!
self.tsize = 2048
self.overlap = 0.5
self.window = signal.getwindow('blackmanharris', self.tsize)
# Band denitions (center freq, span)
self.bands = [
[(1.9e6, 200e3), (3.65e6, 300e3), (7.1e6, 300e3)], # Ch1
[(10.125e6, 50e3), (14.175e6, 350e3)], # Ch2
[(18.1e6, 100e3), (21.2e6, 350e3), (24.94e6, 100e3)], # Ch3
[(28.5e6, 1.7e6), (50.15e6, 500e3)] # Ch4
]
def processchannel(self, iqdata, channelidx):!
"""!
Process I/Q data for one channel, return spectrum for each band!
!
Args:!
iqdata: Complex numpy array (I + jQ)
channelidx: 0-3!
!
Returns:!
List of (freqarray, powerarray) tuples for each band!
"""!
spectra = []!
!
for bandcenter, bandspan in self.bands[channelidx]:
# Tune to band center (already done in FPGA NCO)
# Just perform FFT on decimated data
# Windowing
windowed = iqdata * self.window!
!
# FFT!
spectrum = np.t.tshift(np.t.t(windowed))!
!
# Power in dBm (calibrated)!
# Assumes full-scale ADC = +4 dBm!
powerdbfs = 20 * np.log10(np.abs(spectrum) / self.tsize)!
powerdbm = powerdbfs + 4.0 # Calibration oset!
!
# Frequency axis!
fs = 250e3 # Sample rate after decimation!
freq = np.linspace(-fs/2, fs/2, self.tsize) + bandcenter!
!
spectra.append((freq, powerdbm))
return spectra
def updatedisplay(self, allchanneldata):!
"""!
Update waterfall for all channels!
Called at ~10 Hz rate!
"""!
for chidx, iqdata in enumerate(allchanneldata):!
spectra = self.processchannel(iqdata, chidx)
for bandidx, (freq, power) in enumerate(spectra):!
# Update waterfall plot!
self.waterfallwidgets[chidx][band_idx].update(freq, power)!

**Competitive Advantages:**
1. **True simultaneous multi-band** (most competitors scan or have limited
channels)
2. **Open-source FPGA design** (customizable DSP)
3. **Modular architecture** (easy to repair/upgrade)
4. **Lower cost** (50-60% of commercial)
**Disadvantages:**
1. **Lower ADC clipping threshold** (+4 dBm vs. +10-20 dBm commercial)
2. **No built-in transmitter** (RX only)
3. **Requires external computer** (no built-in display/controls)
4. **Prototype/DIY aesthetic** (vs. polished commercial)
Risk Mitigation Strategies
**Technical Risks:**!
1. **Oscillation in cascaded ampliers:**
- Mitigation: Rigorous K-factor analysis in design phase!
- Add series resistors (10) and ferrite beads prophylactically!
- Build single-channel prototype rst, verify stability before scaling!
2. **ADC overload more common than expected:**
- Mitigation: Implement AGC in rmware (already planned)!
- User can enable/disable per-band AGC!
- Log overload events to help user tune antenna coupling!
3. **Filter tuning too critical for reproducibility:**
- Mitigation: Design wider tolerance lters (sacrice 3 dB stopband rejection for easier0
production)!
- Use only C0G/NP0 capacitors (5% tolerance acceptable with redesign)!
- Document tuning procedure with photos/videos!
- Provide pre-tuned lter modules as option (higher cost)!
4. DSP48 resource exhaustion despite time-multiplexing:!
- Mitigation: Reduce FIR lter length (127 63 taps)!
- Accept slightly worse stopband (-100 dB -80 dB, still adequate)!
- Alternative: Use distributed arithmetic for FIR (trades LUTs for DSP48s)!
- Worst case: Process only 3 channels simultaneously, time-share 4th!
5. Thermal runaway in high-power ampliers:!
- Mitigation: Temperature monitoring via thermistors!
- Automatic power reduction if T > 70C!
- Forced air cooling for rack-mount version!
- Use ampliers with thermal shutdown (e.g., GALI series)!
6. EMI/RFI causing spurious signals:!
- Mitigation: Full enclosure shielding (6-sided)!
- Separate power domains for analog/digital!
- Common-mode chokes on all external cables!
- EMC testing before production (FCC Part 15 Class A)!
7. SW/AM Broadcast breakthrough despite ltering:!
- Mitigation: Add user-controllable notch lters!
- Software-dened adaptive ltering in FPGA!
- Accept slight desensitization in exchange for clean spectrum!
- Document "known interference" frequencies for user awareness!
Supply Chain Risks:!
1. Component obsolescence (especially Mini-Circuits MMIC):!
- Mitigation: Design with pin-compatible alternatives documented!
- Buy 1-year supply for critical parts (MAR/ERA series)!
- Maintain relationships with distributors (Digi-Key, Mouser)!
- Second-source all ampliers where possible!
2. PCB fabrication delays:!
- Mitigation: Use multiple fab houses (JLCPCB, PCBWay, OSH Park)!
- Maintain tested Gerber les with multiple vendors!
- Allow 3-4 week lead time in project schedule!
- Order extra bare PCBs (5-10) for rework/testing!
3. FPGA/SoC supply constraints:!
- Mitigation: Eclypse Z7 uses Zynq-7020 (mature product, widely available)!
- Alternative boards: PYNQ-Z2, Arty Z7 (lower cost, similar capability)!
- Design FPGA code to be portable across Zynq family!
- Purchase development board immediately (long lead times possible)!
Market/Business Risks:!
1. Limited market size (amateur radio operators):!
- Mitigation: Target additional markets:!
* Academic/research (spectrum monitoring)!
* Radio astronomy (Jovian/solar observations)!
* SIGINT/monitoring enthusiasts!
* Industrial (RF spectrum surveillance)!
- Open-source nature attracts DIY community!
- Sell as kit (lower price point, higher margin)!
2. Competition from cheap Chinese SDRs (RSP, Airspy):!
- Mitigation: Emphasize unique features:!
* True simultaneous multi-band (vs. sequential scanning)!
* Open FPGA design (hackable, customizable)!
* Better overload protection than typical SDRs!
* Community support/documentation!
- Target mid-tier market ($500-1000)!
- Oer customization services for commercial users!
3. Software/rmware development delays:!
- Mitigation: Release hardware rst with basic functionality!
* Phase 1: Raw I/Q streaming to PC (GNU Radio compatible)!
* Phase 2: Basic demodulators (SSB, CW, AM)!
* Phase 3: Advanced features (AGC, NR, waterfall)!
- Leverage existing open-source SDR software (gqrx, SDR++)!
- Build active developer community (GitHub, forums)!

Pre-Integration Testing (Individual Modules):!
- [ ] All lters: S-parameters within 1 dB of simulation!

- [ ] Combiners: Isolation > 20 dB, insertion loss < 5.5 dB!
- [ ] Active splitter: Gain +11 dB 1 dB, NF < 4 dB!
System Integration Testing:!
- [ ] Single-tone frequency response: at 1.5 dB per band!
- [ ] Multi-tone IMD: < -50 dBc @ -20 dBm input per tone!
- [ ] Sensitivity: MDS < -120 dBm (2.5 kHz BW, 10 dB SNR)!
- [ ] Overload: No clipping at +0 dBm input (any band)!
- [ ] AGC response time: 10 ms attack, 100 ms decay!
- [ ] Cross-channel isolation: > 40 dB between channels!
- [ ] Temperature stability: < 2 dB gain change (-10C to +60C)!
FPGA/Software Testing:!
- [ ] DSP48 utilization < 90% (headroom for future features)!
- [ ] DMA throughput: sustained 4 MB/s (all channels)!
- [ ] FFT display: update rate > 10 Hz, no dropped frames!
- [ ] AGC control: relay switching < 50 ms latency!
- [ ] Peak detector: < 1% error vs. true peak!
Reliability Testing:!
- [ ] 48-hour burn-in: no parameter drift > 2 dB!
- [ ] 100 power cycles: no intermittent failures!
- [ ] ESD testing: survives 2 kV contact discharge (IEC 61000-4-2)!
- [ ] Vibration: survives 1G sine sweep 5-500 Hz!
EMC Compliance Testing:!
- [ ] Radiated emissions: < FCC Part 15 Class A limits!
